  "prompt": "Are there any applications for a Chromebook that I can use to make applications for Google Cardboard?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several ways to develop Google Cardboard applications on a Chromebook:\n\n1. Unity\n- Can be used through Linux (Beta) on Chrome OS\n- Supports Google Cardboard VR development\n- Free version available\n\n2. A-Frame\n- Web-based VR framework\n- Works directly in Chrome browser\n- Uses HTML/JavaScript\n- No installation required\n\n3. Android Studio\n- Can be installed via Linux (Beta) on Chrome OS\n- Supports Cardboard/VR app development for Android\n- Full development environment\n\n4. WebVR/WebXR\n- Browser-based VR development\n- Works directly on Chromebook\n- Uses JavaScript and HTML5\n\n5. Godot Engine\n- Open-source game engine\n- Can be installed via Linux (Beta)\n- Supports VR development\n\nImportant note: For the most robust development experience, you'll want to:\n- Enable Linux (Beta) in Chromebook settings\n- Ensure your Chromebook supports Linux apps\n- Have sufficient processing power and storage\n\nEach method has different complexity levels, so choose based on your programming experience and specific project requirements.",
